  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Alfa Laval MAB series centrifuges are <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/">disc-stack-type centrifuges</a> with a solid bowl. A solid-bowl centrifuge implies that the separated solids must be manually removed periodically.
  </p>
  <p>
    These are very simple centrifuges, with the main disadvantage of MAB-type centrifuges being the 'manual cleaning' operation that requires the centrifuge to be stopped.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Alfa Laval MAB Series Centrifuges are solid-retaining (also known as solid bowl or manual-clean) disc centrifuges ideal for the continuous, three-phase separation of fuels, such as <a href="/diesel-centrifuge/">diesel</a>, <a href="/biodiesel-centrifuge/">biodiesel</a>, <a href="/lube-oil-centrifuge/">turbine lube oil</a>, and hydraulic oil.
  </p>

  <h2 id="applications">Applications</h2>
  <p>
    The Alfa Laval MAB centrifuge is a purifier version of a disc-stack centrifuge. It is specifically designed to purify water from mineral oils and fuels such as diesel fuel, turbine lube oil, hydraulic oil, engine oil, etc.
  </p>

  <h2 id="operation">Operation</h2>
  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
    <div>
      <p>
        The process fluid is fed to the rotating centrifuge bowl from the top <strong>(1)</strong> and is sped up in the distributor <strong>(2)</strong>. It then enters the disc stack <strong>(3)</strong>, and it is between the discs that the separation occurs.
      </p>
      <p>
        The high centrifugal force pushes the water and heavy solids to the bowl wall. The solids accumulate here, and the water fluid travels over the top disc <strong>(4)</strong> and exits the bowl through the open outlet <strong>(5)</strong>. The oil (light phase) is moved towards the bowl center and exits the bowl through the open outlet <strong>(6)</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The centrifuge needs to be periodically stopped for manual removal of separated solids. The rotating bowl assembly is mounted on a vertical 'bowl-spindle' <strong>(7)</strong>. A horizontally mounted motor rotates the spindle via a worm gear.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div>
